    en: "New York regulates children's camps under 10 NYCRR Part 7 (Children's Camps), with enforcement by local county health departments under Public Health Law Article 13-B. Monroe County Department of Public Health inspects and licenses camps in the Rochester area. A children's camp is defined as any program that cares for 5 or more children between the ages of 3 and 17 for at least 3 hours a day and 3 or more days in a row. Day camps (children return home each night) and overnight camps (children sleep at camp) both fall under the rules. Sports camps, arts camps, religious camps, and specialty camps are all covered. Small programs operated by schools as after-school care (covered under School Age Child Care rules), programs for children only 2 years old or younger, and camps that operate fewer than 3 consecutive days are typically exempt. Key rules include: (1) Staff-to-camper ratios depend on age — 1:8 for 6-7 year olds, 1:10 for 8-9 year olds, 1:12 for 10-14 year olds, 1:15 for 15-17 year olds. Overnight camps require slightly lower ratios. (2) Camp directors must be 21 or older with appropriate supervisory experience. Counselors must be 16 or older. Assistant counselors (called counselors-in-training, CITs) can be 14 to 15 but cannot be left alone with campers. (3) All staff working directly with children must pass a background check including NY State Central Register (SCR) for child abuse history, sex offender registry check, and criminal history. (4) Aquatic activities (swimming, boating) require certified lifeguards at specified ratios and specific safety equipment. An overnight camp with swimming must have lifeguards on duty whenever the water is in use. (5) Emergency action plans for fire, severe weather, medical emergencies, lost camper, and evacuation must be posted and practiced. (6) Medical personnel or first aid-trained staff must be on site. Overnight camps require a camp health director who is typically a registered nurse. (7) Food service must meet the NY Sanitary Code. A camp serving meals requires a food service permit and periodic inspection. (8) Camps must carry liability insurance with minimum coverage levels. To verify a camp's license, Monroe County Department of Public Health maintains a searchable database. A parent can also ask the camp director for the current Camp Operating Permit and inspection report. Inspection reports are public records and show any violations from the most recent inspection. Common violations the inspector looks for: expired food, unsafe playground equipment, missing or incomplete emergency plans, staff background check gaps, inadequate ratios, and unsanitary conditions. If a parent discovers a safety issue or suspected abuse at a camp, options include: (1) Report to the camp director first and ask for corrective action, (2) Report to the Monroe County Department of Public Health Camp Program at [number being verified] for code violations, (3) Report to the NY Statewide Central Register of Child Abuse and Maltreatment at [number being verified] for suspected abuse, (4) Report to law enforcement for any criminal conduct, (5) Consult with Legal Aid or a personal injury attorney for a child who was injured. A camp can lose its license for repeated violations. The DOH can order immediate closure for imminent harm. A parent has the right to a refund of camp fees if the camp closes mid-season due to licensing issues. Most camp enrollment contracts include a cancellation policy — a parent withdrawing a child early usually forfeits a portion of the fees depending on how much notice was given and whether the spot was filled by another family. For children's camps in other NY counties, the local county health department handles licensing and enforcement."
